2.1.1.2 Harmonisation algorithm

To compute h_diabetes from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • some hedimX == 7 into 1
  • -9 into 997
  • -8 into 998
  • otherwise into 0

To compute h_diabetes_age from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • if h_diabetes == 1, h_diabetes_age = heagd
  • if h_diabetes == 0, h_diabetes_age = 996
  • -9 into 997
  • -8 into 998
  • otherwise, h_diabetes_age = 999

R script:

# Categorical variable harmonization
ELSA_ds_w1 <- tibble(id = ELSA_w1$id)
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes <- rep(0, length(ELSA_w1$id))
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes[which((ELSA_w1$hedim01 == 7 | ELSA_w1$hedim02 == 7 | ELSA_w1$hedim03 == 
    7 | ELSA_w1$hedim04 == 7 | ELSA_w1$hedim05 == 7 | ELSA_w1$hedim06 == 7 | 
    ELSA_w1$hedim07 == 7))] <- 1
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes[which(ELSA_w1$hedim01 == -9)] <- 997
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes[which(ELSA_w1$hedim01 == -8)] <- 998

# Continuous variable harmonization
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes_age <- rep(999, length(ELSA_w1$id))
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes == 0)] <- 996
ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes == 1)] <- car::recode(ELSA_w1$heagd[which(ELSA_ds_w1$h_diabetes == 
    1)], "-1=996;-8=998;-9=997")

# Global table
ELSA_ds <- ELSA_ds_w1

2.1.2.2 Harmonisation algorithm

To compute h_diabetes from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • h_diabetes w1 == 1 or some hedimX == 7 into 1
  • h_diabetes w1 != 1 and hedia01 == -9 and hedimX == -1 into 997
  • h_diabetes w1 != 1 and hedia01 == -8 and hedimX == -1 into 998
  • otherwise into 0

To compute h_diabetes_age from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • if h_diabetes == 1, h_diabetes_age = HeAgd
  • if h_diabetes == 0, h_diabetes_age = 996
  • -9 into 997
  • -8 into 998
  • otherwise, h_diabetes_age = 999

R script:

ELSA_w2 <- left_join(ELSA_w2, ELSA_ds, by = "id")

# Categorical variable harmonization
ELSA_ds_w2 <- tibble(id = ELSA_w2$id)
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes <- rep(0, length(ELSA_w2$id))
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes[which((ELSA_w2$h_diabetes == 1 | ELSA_w2$hedim01 == 7 | 
    ELSA_w2$hedim02 == 7 | ELSA_w2$hedim03 == 7 | ELSA_w2$hedim04 == 7 | ELSA_w2$hedim05 == 
    7 | ELSA_w2$hedim06 == 7 | ELSA_w2$hedim07 == 7 | ELSA_w2$hedim08 == 7))] <- 1
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes[which((ELSA_w2$h_diabetes != 1 | is.na(ELSA_w2$h_diabetes)) & 
    ELSA_w2$hedia01 == -9 & ELSA_w2$hedim01 == -1)] <- 997
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes[which((ELSA_w2$h_diabetes != 1 | is.na(ELSA_w2$h_diabetes)) & 
    ELSA_w2$hedia01 == -8 & ELSA_w2$hedim01 == -1)] <- 998

# Continuous variable harmonization
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes_age <- rep(999, length(ELSA_w2$id))
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes == 0)] <- 996
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes == 1)] <- car::recode(ELSA_w2$HeAgd[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes == 
    1)], "-1=996;-8=998;-9=997")
ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes == 1 & !is.na(ELSA_w2$h_diabetes_age) & 
    !ELSA_w2$h_diabetes_age %in% miss_values_vector)] <- ELSA_w2$h_diabetes_age[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes == 
    1 & !is.na(ELSA_w2$h_diabetes_age) & !ELSA_w2$h_diabetes_age %in% miss_values_vector)]

# Update of global table
assign_merge <- function(endtib, sttib, log_vec = c(T), col_end_index = NULL, 
    col_st_index = NULL) {
    newtib <- full_join(endtib, sttib, by = "id")
    row.names(newtib) <- newtib$id
    newtib[log_vec, col_end_index] <- newtib[log_vec, col_st_index]
    id_ind <- match("id", names(newtib))
    newtib <- newtib[, c(id_ind, col_end_index)]
    names(newtib)[2] <- "x"
    newtib$x <- car::recode(newtib$x, "NA=999")
    names(newtib)[2] <- names(endtib)[col_end_index]
    newtib
}
ELSA_ds_prov <- ELSA_ds[, c(1, 2)]
ELSA_ds_prov <- assign_merge(ELSA_ds_prov, ELSA_ds_w2, log_vec = ELSA_ds_w2$id, 
    col_end_index = 2, col_st_index = 3)
ELSA_ds_aux <- ELSA_ds[, c(1, 3)]
ELSA_ds_aux <- assign_merge(ELSA_ds_aux, ELSA_ds_w2, log_vec = ELSA_ds_w2$id[which(ELSA_ds_w2$h_diabetes != 
    999)], col_end_index = 2, col_st_index = 4)
ELSA_ds <- ELSA_ds_prov
ELSA_ds$h_diabetes_age <- ELSA_ds_aux$h_diabetes_age
rm(ELSA_ds_prov)
rm(ELSA_ds_aux)

2.1.3.2 Harmonisation algorithm

To compute h_diabetes from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • h_diabetes previous == 1 or dhedimdi == 1 into 1
  • h_diabetes previous != 1 and dhedimdi == 0 into 0
  • h_diabetes previous != 1 and dhedimdi == -1 into 996
  • otherwise into 999

To compute h_diabetes_age from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • if h_diabetes == 1, h_diabetes_age = heagd
  • if h_diabetes == 0, h_diabetes_age = 996
  • -9 into 997
  • -8 into 998
  • otherwise, h_diabetes_age = 999

R script:

ELSA_w3 <- left_join(ELSA_w3, ELSA_ds, by = "id")

# Categorical variable harmonization
ELSA_ds_w3 <- tibble(id = ELSA_w3$id)
ELSA_ds_w3$h_diabetes <- rep(999, length(ELSA_w3$id))
ELSA_ds_w3$h_diabetes[which((ELSA_w3$h_diabetes != 1 | is.na(ELSA_w3$h_diabetes)) & 
    (ELSA_w3$dhedimdi == 0))] <- 0

# Update of global table
assign_merge <- function(endtib, sttib, log_vec = c(T), col_end_index = NULL, 
    col_st_index = NULL) {
    newtib <- full_join(endtib, sttib, by = "id")
    row.names(newtib) <- newtib$id
    newtib[log_vec, col_end_index] <- newtib[log_vec, col_st_index]
    id_ind <- match("id", names(newtib))
    newtib <- newtib[, c(id_ind, col_end_index)]
    names(newtib)[2] <- "x"
    newtib$x <- car::recode(newtib$x, "NA=999")
    names(newtib)[2] <- names(endtib)[col_end_index]
    newtib
}

2.1.4.2 Harmonisation algorithm

To compute h_diabetes from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • h_diabetes previous == 1 or hedimdi == 1 into 1
  • h_diabetes previous != 1 and hedimdi == 0 into 0
  • h_diabetes previous != 1 and hedimdi == -8 into 998
  • h_diabetes previous != 1 and hedimdi == -9 into 997
  • otherwise into 999

To compute h_diabetes_age from the study-specific variable it has to be recoded as follows:

  • if h_diabetes == 1, h_diabetes_age = heagd
  • if h_diabetes == 0, h_diabetes_age = 996
  • -9 into 997
  • -8 into 998
  • otherwise, h_diabetes_age = 999

2.2 Summary of descriptive statistics of the harmonised variable accross populations and waves

Two tables are generated:

  1. Percentages of categories in each harmonised variable.

  2. Frequencies and percentages of individuals with different trajectories. To avoid too large table, Only trajectories with percentages larger than 0.3 are shown.

for (name in names(l.hds)) {
    aux_object <- l.hds[[name]]
    label(l.hds[[name]][[2]]) <- label(aux_object[[2]]) <- ds_label  # Text value assigned at the DS description, at the top
    l.hds[[name]][[2]] <- labelled(l.hds[[name]][[2]], labels = cat_label)
    label(l.hds[[name]][[3]]) <- label(aux_object[[3]]) <- ds_label_age  # Text value assigned at the DS description, at the top
    l.hds[[name]][[3]] <- labelled(l.hds[[name]][[3]], labels = cont_label)
    aux_object[[2]] <- car::recode(aux_object[[2]], "miss_values_vector=NA")
    aux_object[[2]] <- labelled(aux_object[[2]], labels = cat_label[1:2])
    m_name <- paste0("ELSA_m_ds_", name)
    assign(m_name, aux_object)
    rm(aux_object)
}

3 Quality estimation

  • We assume that if an individual answers it has diabetes in one wave, it has diabetes for all the next waves. Individuals with discrepancies with respect to this criterium are specified at the end of each validation.
  • From wave 2 on, the variable hedimdi is chosen instead of the variables hedia0x, x=1,...,9/hediadi of wave 2.
